[3] Michigan
Date: Thu 8 Nov 2018, 9:16 AM EST
Source: WZZM [edited]
https://www.wzzm13.com/article/news/health/kent-county-now-included-in-statewide-hepatitis-a-outbreak/69-612569596


With 899 cases of hepatitis A reported in Michigan in the outbreak [since August 2016], it should come as no surprise some of those cases are in Kent County. The Kent County Health Department was recently notified of a 4th case that is linked to this outbreak. Because the case was diagnosed within 100 days of a previous case, Kent County is now listed as part of the state's outbreak jurisdiction.

According to a press release, Michigan Department of Health and Human Services identifies geographic areas within the outbreak jurisdiction as those where there is a potential for ongoing transmission of hepatitis A.

"Kent County normally sees about 1 case of hepatitis A per year," says Adam London, Administrative Health Officer at KCHD. "In 2018 we have had 8 cases so far, including 4 of the same genotype. It is a reminder about how communicable this illness is and that we need to be vigilant about protecting ourselves and our loved ones."

